,Recommended,249630,15788132,"Posted: 11 May, 2015",all,Rusyn,"Well done in comparison to most early access titles, Delver manages to keep a simplistic approach to gameplay yet keeps you coming back for more runs. The game allows little room for building your character as you progress, and you are left at the game's mercy when it comes to gear. As you progress deeper into the games dungeon, your play style will rely almost solely on what weapons and armor you find and your luck with the random level generator.Still, the game is a real-time roguelike experience, and much like classic roguelikes, you will often find yourself backpedaling into doorways while trying to kite varied and numerous enemies. It's easy to catch yourself reserving all of your ranged attacks (wands rely on finite charges and bows rely on a rare stock of arrows) for dire circumstances, while searching constantly for a better melee weapon. Armor can be hit or miss, and is often a trade-off between movement speed and protection (both of which are very effective).From death to death, your gold will carry over. The only opportunity to buy items and spells is at the beginning of each run. While the dungeon is currently very short (only seven floors), the environments are nicely varied and the randomly generated rooms keeps it feeling fresh with each attempt. It's worth the price."
,Recommended,249630,10927722,"Posted: 28 June, 2014",all,Randomspirits,Great game with a cute super chunky (pixel) artstyle. Has really nice music as well.
76561198126340720,Not Recommended,249630,17179316,"Posted: 22 July, 2015",all,CJwat11,"God horrible. Sure, it has a great combat system, loads of items, and heck, even a great boss fight! However, this game consists of many flaws that ruin the gameplay.1. No Jump Buttons2. Bats that have the glitchiest movement patterns in any game.3. Crazy damage after picking up the Orb, I had full platemail and 60 health, but monsters were still dealing like 6-8 damage! Not the melee, I was fine with that, but the mages were just shooting spell after spell after spell, you couldn't even say ""I'm dead"" before you're dead.This is supposed to be a rogue game, but only problem. UNFAIR CHALLENGE, you want something fair? Go play Crypt of the Necrodancer, and avoid this abysmal failure for ""challenge"".P.S: This is Early Access, so it will have bugs, but this is way TOO many."
76561198014229134,Recommended,249630,13216082,"Posted: 3 December, 2014",all,Dorok,"Short light non nasty Roguelike with some cool mood of Ultima Underworld. It is still in early access but it is already very playable and in fact very fun to play and replay and replay. :-) Don't excpt a very deep gameplay but also don't let your first feeling and first 2/3 attempts misguide you, it's not a superficial game and it has already mutliple gameplay elements quite tuned. I just post this short short review for the thumb up, but for sure I will make a new review a bit more deep for the release version."
76561197999795539,Recommended,249630,21396367,"Posted: 22 February, 2016",all,Veskaida,"Delver feels like a well-polished beta for a game that is nearing completion, which feels really good in a Steam full of early access games left unfinished. I highly recommend playing it if you enjoy fantasy-themed dungeon crawlers or rogue-likes.It runs smoothly with very few glitchs/bugs, and has a great art style and enemy design with excellent semi-randomized levels. The music is spectacular, being in a ""simplistic retro"" style. The only issues I experienced were with some of the newer levels creating inescapable sub-sections (because of ladders not generating). Player level progression could use an overhaul, since some stats and playstyles don't feel powerful enough, but nothing feels blatantly overpowered, so that can get fixed easily.The game feels complete until halfway through, and without spoilers after that there are several levels which ATM feel like ""kill screens"" in that they are so small, with the enemy spawn rate being so high, and being in claustrophobic environments.Once you beat the game (or die) your equipped items, inventory, and character levels dissapear, with only your gold being preserved. So a ""level+"" mode would be a nice touch for beating the game. Also ATM you can buy items from shops, but not sell.It also has a simple but effective level editor, if you're into that."
