76561197979061816,Recommended,249630,8536273,"Posted: 3 January, 2014",all,Scrooloose,"Delver is definitely worth playing. Think, Legend of Grimrock meets Minecraft...You'll start off as an adventurer in a camp with a random set of gear to get you started. This camp holds shop keepers who can sell you items that will help you on your way, the catch is you probably can't afford anything they sell.Ok so, the deal is this... You start with basically nothing, a pair of ""useless pants"" and leather armor, an iron dagger, a random magic wand, and a random potion. This means no money, and very little to get you going. However as you play through Delver's brilliantly crafted, procedurally generated levels you'll find gear pretty quickly, and also gold. Once you enter the dungeon there is no leaving until you complete the dungeon, or die. I.E. no going back to to town to restock potions or buy new items.What use is there in having a town in the first place? Well, when you die you lose everything and start a new random dungeon, --but you keep your gold--. So should you die, perhaps you can now afford to buy an amulet with extra armor, or a better weapon to start with. Maybe a scroll of healing, or if you have enough money you can purchase a ""skill in a jar"" basically a level up. So camp can be pretty helpful if your just having a rough time finding things to get you through. Just keep in mind when you die again these items are lost.So far Delver has only seven floors. I'm hoping that the devs will add more in the future or perhaps make a sort of new game plus mode. In the meantime though, these seven floors are challenging. Hallways, blind corners, randomized traps, enemies from nowhere, and darkness work together to foil your attempts to make it to the next floor. When you finally do make it the floor seven and find the treasure you then have to fight your way back to the top floor with harder enemies spawning all around you.Fighting your way back to the top is almost panic inducing, as you will quickly find yourself scrounging for everly last item, potion and scrap of food, making the final door to the end of the game feel pretty damn satisfying, and fueling an urge to do it all over again.For the love of all that is good play Delver.I for one am looking ever forward to more and more updates to what promises to be a great old school dungeon crawler."
