,Recommended,249630,8543577,"Posted: 3 January, 2014",all,That Guy,"This is an early impression and not necessarily a ""review.""Delver is a simplistic first person roguelike with very Minecraft-y graphics.  The first couple of levels are easy but later levels include more agile and clever enemies, especially ranged enemies that like to circle strafe and are difficult to hit.  I'm actually impressed by the conversion of a roguelike to the first person perspective as a lot of roguelike tactics have converted seamlessly: move conservatively, use your items liberally, and lure enemies into hallways to fight them one at a time.When you die, you lose all your equipment but your gold carries over, allowing you to purchase items at the surface shop.  There are a couple of issues I have with the overall design that stem from the simplistic nature.  Specifically, the attributes are seemingly useless with health being the most important as your HP does not increase as you level.  Due to the naure of the random levels, it's very easy for a trap to be placed in a one tile hallway forcing you to walk over it.  This can possibly lead to unbeatable levels as a teleport trap is unavoidable but I have yet to encounter an impossible dungeon.For an early access beta, I'm very impressed.  Delver isn't very feature deep right now but there's plenty of room for it to grow."
