,Recommended,249630,10813252,"Posted: 25 June, 2014",all,ʜᴏᴍᴀɢᴇ,"First and foremost, I will say that although I personally find this game's simple visual style and interface quite appealing (although it could use some sort of noclip mechanic to help with getting stuck in terrain), it occasionally makes me nauseous while playing for more than a few minutes.As a fan of brutally difficult roguelike and platformer games, as well as difficult games in general (I love NetHack, Spelunky, The Binding of Isaac, the original arcade version of Ghosts n' Goblins, etc.), I bought this game due to the ""roguelike"" tag.Every item is Delver is identified before you even pick it up, save for potions (identified after drinking the first of that color).  And there is only one negative potion effect out of six or so, a weak poison that is easily counteracted by eating any piece of food.Delver has only 7 dungeon floors to its name, which are procedurally generated, true, save for the last, which is actually a fixed map.  Delver also lacks shopkeepers on floors, instead, there are only two NPCs, and they are on the surface above the dungeon.  So your character ends up carrying a bunch of gold with no way to spend it except by returning to the start or dying.When dying in Delver, you lose everything except your gold.  This gives you a chance to buy an item when you start a new game to give you an edge, but the high prices ensure that you cannot buy a good item on every run.The enemies in the first levels of Delver are relative pushovers (as well as possessing primitive AI that can only charge at the player in a straight line, think Minecraft Beta hostile mobs).  Most enemies in the game supposedly have no more than 4 HP, but player attacks seem to deal a lot less damage than they should according to weapon descriptions.  Charging attacks makes them hit every time, which makes fast charging weapons like daggers and shortswords much more effective than larger weapons like hammers or swords.The enemies get more advanced as you proceed, starting with bandits and slimes and advancing to spiders and floating squid things, orcs and worms, and eventually skeletons and floating skulls.  Zombies and worms can cause the poison effect, which damages health.  Though the enemies are nice so far, there are issues with surround sound in this game.  Bandits commonly yell threats as they see you, but the sound seems to come out of the opposite speaker of their direction, e.g. I hear ""You're dead!"" out of my rear right speaker, when the bandit is actually approaching from my left.  Given how much I've come to rely on surround sound in this type of game, this can be frustrating.**** the mages on the first two levels.  I have died to those guys way too many times.  Enemies cannot use bows, only magic and melee.  Melee enemies are easy to deal with, but magic can get annoying.  More annoying is the death screen, which often prevents you from knowing what exactly killed you.  This means you don't necessarily know what you did wrong to get you killed.The level up system has six stats.  Each time you level up, the game randomly chooses three for you to pick from to increase.  Health, attack, defense, speed, agility (attack speed), and magic (increases wand charges and wand damage).  I find that health is always a priority.  I try to get my health to 16, then start putting points into speed and agility.  Attack, defense, and magic are usually made obsolete due to finding better equipment.  Note that to my knowledge, the other stats also increase by a small amount on level up, but the one you pick goes up by much more than the others.Though this game is simple, it is not necessarily easy every run.  I can see this game getting much better once all the glitches with getting stuck in terrain are fixed.  I find that this game is actually quite fun if you are into dungeon crawling and exploration, and the surplus of loot is due to the ending.  At the end, you need to escape the dungeon with the treasure while being pursued by endless skeletons and skeleton mages, currently the hardest respawning enemies in the game, in addition to the extremely fast and mobile floating skulls.  The many supplies you find on your way down are basically preparation for this difficult rush section.  Upgrading speed comes in extreme handy for this action packed portion of the game.  The game has limited enemies and environments, but it is in beta and the soundtrack is solid as-is, and the enemies have enough diversity to vary with the current levels.Most of the enemies with AI that only charges straight at you are gone after the first two levels.Features I would like to see added:Noclip or some other system to deal with getting stuck in terrain without having to delete your saveBetter bandit AISpiders should deal poison instead of worms (It's gaming tradition!)Many more floorsMore level varietyMore enemiesEnemies that use bowsMore gold, shopkeepers and NPCs on floorsArmor with secondary effectsSomething that fits in the glove slot, which is currently unusedMore bosses and maybe even minibossesMore types of trapsMore hidden doors and passagesEaster eggsLocal or online co-op could be really awesome if done right (of course, the difficulty level would have to drastically increase as well)I won't put PvP arena on here because it wouldn't add to the game IMO.  Delver is a PvE type game."
