,Recommended,249630,19985583,"Posted: 26 December, 2015",all,majikthise,"I'm really happy I picked up Delver. I had low expectations, but Delver has turned out to be one of the best roguelike dungeon crawlers I've played in quite a while. It's simple, and the graphics harken back to Daggerfall days, but it shines where it counts:- Dungeons are randomly generated (with some exceptions) and feel WORTH exploring. Maps are loaded with crevasses, bridges, hidden rooms, lava, underground lakes, traps, and more. Many maps have a 3D element to them, with bridges or loopbacks bringing you under or over an area you just walked through, or dark passages descending into gloom. If you're a completionist, there is true value in exploring every niche and nook, as the game will reward you with life-saving loot!- Loot! The loot system has more depth than you might guess. It's not Diablo, but there are some elements of the random-loot system here. The game will surprise you with finely crafted items from time to time, or weapons with elemental attacks, usually with some negative trait alongside (Broken 1-3 dmg dagger, with +3 ice damage). You have just enough space in your inventory that by dungeon level 5-6, you might have a full load (and no junk). This means careful inventory management.- Permadeth! You only die once, however you keep some of your money after death. This is useful in shops.Some other things to like about Delver:- Runs ridiculous framerates on my Macbook Pro and never even turns on the fan! My poor laptop isn't much of a gaming rig, but Delver apparently doesn't need one. It's easily the fastest and most responsive FPS-view game I own.- Loads and quits in seconds. You can boot the game and be playing in less than 10 seconds. To quit: ESC, Save, ESC drops you straight to desktop in about 3 seconds!Conclusion: Delver is an excellent choice for people who like RPG's, roguelikes, and exploration. It's lighthearted, but not dumbed-down or easy."
